Duck typing is a technique in which dynamic languages use to check at run-time the type of an object. It requires that the code to be flexible enough to operate on objects of any type that satisfies a set of requirements, regardless of the specific type of the object.
TypeScript is a typed language (static typing), but many people consider it more expressive than Java because it allows you to write less code to achieve the same result.
In TypeScript:

interface Animal {
    speak(): string;
}
interface Dog extends Animal {
    wagTail(): void;
}
class Cat implements Animal {
    speak(): string {
        return "Meow!";
    }
}
class Dog {
    wagTail(): void {
        console.log("Wagging my tail");
    }
}
let animal: Animal = new Cat(); // OK
let dog: Dog = new Dog(); // OK
animal = new Dog(); // ERROR
